<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>AspNet MVC on Codewrecks</title><link>https://www.codewrecks.com/categories/aspnet-mvc/</link><description>Recent content in AspNet MVC on Codewrecks</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 20 Apr 2009 10:00:37 +0200</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://www.codewrecks.com/categories/aspnet-mvc/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Decouple controllers and other objects from context in aspnet mvc</title><link>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/decouple-controllers-and-other-objects-from-context-in-aspnet-mvc/</link><pubDate>Mon, 20 Apr 2009 10:00:37 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/decouple-controllers-and-other-objects-from-context-in-aspnet-mvc/</guid><description>&lt;p>When I decided to write down a little class to manage a &lt;a href="http://www.codewrecks.com/blog/index.php/2009/04/14/build-a-menu-for-aspnet-mvc-site/">menu&lt;/a>, I created a simple object that reads the menu data in xml, and transform it into a series of MenuItem object. The first thing I wanted to do is writing some test to verify that the logic is ok, but since my class uses Url.RouteUrl to build the url from the controller and action strings, testing becomes difficult, because it does not runs outside iis.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Aspnet Mvc plus jQuery client template engine have fun with them</title><link>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/aspnet-mvc-plus-jquery-client-template-engine-have-fun-with-them/</link><pubDate>Wed, 15 Apr 2009 10:00:37 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/aspnet-mvc-plus-jquery-client-template-engine-have-fun-with-them/</guid><description>&lt;p>jQuery has really a lot of interesting plugins, but the one I like most is a template engine called &lt;a href="http://jtemplates.tpython.com/">jtemplates&lt;/a>. Basically it consist of a jQuery extension that is capable of rendering html with javascript on client machine. You really have a lot of flexibility on how to specify a template, basically you can embed it into an &lt;a href="http://jtemplates.tpython.com/example2.html">hidden textarea&lt;/a>, the one you see in the above sample is created in this way&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Build a menu for aspnet mvc site</title><link>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/build-a-menu-for-aspnet-mvc-site/</link><pubDate>Tue, 14 Apr 2009 08:00:37 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/build-a-menu-for-aspnet-mvc-site/</guid><description>&lt;p>I have a little site with mixed webform and mvc pages, and I need a simple way to create a main menu. Since asp.net mvc have the concept of controllers and action I like to express my menu with a simple xml file like this.&lt;/p>
