&lt;p>As you can see the second route is used when the controller need the concept of current page, it is very close to the default one, but it has another parameter called pageid. Now I generate a link to the paged controller with the following code.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Could not load type 8216SystemWebMvcViewPageltltgtrsquo</title><link>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/could-not-load-type-systemwebmvcviewpage/</link><pubDate>Sun, 05 Apr 2009 04:00:37 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://www.codewrecks.com/post/old/2009/04/could-not-load-type-systemwebmvcviewpage/</guid><description>&lt;p>First of all thanks to &lt;a href="http://dotnetmarche.org/blogs/andreabalducci/">Andrea Balducci&lt;/a> that gave me this solution. I have a asp.net application where I enabled Asp.Net mvc following a link in the web. Everything works well until I try to use Strongly Typed View. When I try to have a page that inherits from ViewPage&amp;lt;T&amp;gt; where T is one of my model the system gave me an error of type&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>Could not load type ‘System.Web.Mvc.ViewPage&amp;lt;&amp;hellip;&amp;gt;&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
